<HEAD>Candidate Sounds Like Reformer In Final Weeks Of Presidential
Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At times, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> sounds too much like a reformer to be the presidential candidate of the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has governed <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1929. The 40-year-old candidate preaches democratic reforms and clean elections as he campaigns not so much for the office, which he is certain to win, but to regain his party's lost credibility. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, whose thick black moustache and balding head feature prominently in political cartoons, is described by those close to him as a pragmatist, influenced strongly by his <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> education. Before his nomination last fall as a candidate in the July 6 election, he was President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON>'s budget and planning secretary, a key figure in developing the economic austerity programs that have prevailed in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1982. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> has strong family ties to the northern state of <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leon </LOCATION>, home to political conservatives who oppose the guided economy and government controls dear to governing party ideologues in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Some foes within the party felt <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> would be identified too strongly with the business sector and with conservative groups within the party. But this has worked to the party's advantage. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> has managed to bring private business back into the party fold by advocating fewer government controls and urging business leaders to join the government `` in the battle for world markets.'' `` The time is past when the state was the instrument to solve all of society's problems,'' he told a cheering crowd at a recent meeting of business leaders in <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Nuevo </PERSON> <PERSON> Leon </PERSON>'s capital. He also wants more foreign investment to `` modernize <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> technologically.'' `` What he says agrees with what private business thinks <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> must be,'' said <PERSON> Agustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Legorreta </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Mexican business traditionally has identified with the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, although it must maintain a close relationship with government agencies. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> speaks confidently of the resurgence of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The country has a $ 105 billion foreign debt but has renegotiated it and is keeping up payments. Last month in <LOCATION> Puebla </LOCATION>, a politically conservative state in central <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> de Gortari upset some party officials with his call for reforms. `` The citizens' vote must be respected,'' he said. `` The party will defend its victories, but it must accept its defeats.'' He also promised reforms to encourage more independent judiciary and legislative branches. `` Let us lead the democratic reform the country demands,'' he stated. The political reforms may be difficult because they imply the acceptance by the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> of electoral losses and the consequent loss of power of local or regional party bosses. The party never has lost a presidential election or gubernatorial race in any of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 31 states since its founding. It is generally conceded in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> that the governing party wins elections, but it often is criticized for `` winning'' by more than the necessary votes _ by stuffing ballots to claim overwhelming victories. `` There is a great internal debate going on now,'' said a source close to the candidate. `` <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> is demanding elections free of fraud and there is a lot of pressure being put on local party leaders to be more democratic.'' This year, with the country in the middle of a serious economic crisis, and an increasingly vociferous opposition that includes a dissident group led by former party leaders, those close to <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> believe reforms have a good chance in his six-year term. `` It is better in the long run to win by a small margin than to announce we won by a large margin and lose all credibility,'' said a source in <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' entourage during a recent campaign trip. Some <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> officials privately admit the party may even lose a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat, something that has never happened before. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> won the elections in 1982 for the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> with an official 71 percent of the vote, a figure many considered exaggerated. <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> officials now predict <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> may win the July 6 election with a more realistic 55 percent to 60 percent of the votes. `` We do not know if he will have the freedom to do what he wants to do,'' said <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Junco </PERSON>, publisher of the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Norte </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION> and a frequent government critic. `` But we are condemned to be optimistic evey six years.''
