<HEAD>Pentagon Plans Experimental Rocket Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> plans to build an experimental rocket that would be dropped from a B-52 bomber and used to launch military satellites into space, a newspaper reported Sunday. The three-stage, winged rocket would be dropped about seven miles above the earth and then blast into space, placing payloads of up to 600 pounds into orbit, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported, quoting government and industry experts. Officials have said they hope a prototype will fly next year. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> wants to test the rocket for a program designed to develop light-weight satellites and launchers for various military uses, including spy and communication satellites. The experimental rocket is being pursued by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Projects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which develops futuristic projects for the Pentagon. There is concern on Capitol Hill that the rocket could be launched in secrecy, the Times reported. Although there is an agreement requiring space-faring countries to notify the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> of all payloads going into orbit, the rocket could be fired from remote parts of the world, far from Soviet trawlers and spy satellites that monitor military launchings from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Pentagon has given no indication that it would violate the treaty obligation, but some military officials say privately that it would be useful for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to have the option of quick, secret launchings in the event of war. The Lightsat program, which includes the rocket, is part of a five-year, $ 240 million effort. On May 13, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> signed a letter of contractual intent with <ORGANIZATION> Orbital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> to buy one test rocket, with an option for five more, industry sources say. <ORGANIZATION> Orbital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> would be joined by <ORGANIZATION> Hercules </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> which makes solid-fuel rockets. The three-stage, solid-fuel rocket would weigh 15 tons and measure 50 feet in length. Proponents say the air-launched rocket system would be inexpensive, less vulnerable to attack than ground-based spaceports and ideal for quickly launching small spy satellites to monitor fast-moving battles. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Latham </PERSON>, a former assistant secretary of defense, said: `` The nation looked into air-launched rockets 20 years ago and found them wanting. There are better ways to make systems low cost and survivable.''
