<HEAD>Brass Band to Pay Tribute to Pioneer Madam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN DAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After paying tribute to the nation's war dead in a traditional Memorial Day ceremony, a brass band will wend its way through a pioneer cemetery Monday to salute a 19th century madam called `` the hooker with the heart of gold.'' `` It's tongue-in-cheek,'' said ceremony chairman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> McNichols </PERSON>. `` It's certainly not a part of the formal program.'' <ORGANIZATION> McNichols </ORGANIZATION>' mother for years brought a yellow rose to mark <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s grave as part of a tradition begun by those who had benefited from the madam's charitable donations. <ORGANIZATION> McNichols </ORGANIZATION> and several friends rekindled interest in the generous woman he calls a `` soiled dove.'' The Prospect Hill Preservation Brass Band has played in her memory each Memorial Day since 1980. The 25-piece band will visit Miss <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s grave after the traditional Memorial Day observance at Prospect Hill Cemetery, which sits on a hill near the old <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Trail </LOCATION> where thousands of pioneers pushed their way west past <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. Miss <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> ran the city's highest-priced house of ill-repute for about 30 years. She retired from the business in the mid-1890s, investing her money in real estate. Miss <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> died in 1911, soon after giving her former house of prostitution to the city for use as a hospital. Her will left an estate valued at $ 1 million to be divided among the city, hospitals, a mission, children's charities and the cemetery. The madam-turned-philanthropist is buried among some of the leading citizens of her time _ judges, doctors, politicians, ministers and brewery barons. `` Everybody that was anybody is buried in that cemetery,'' said <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumann </PERSON>, president of the cemetery foundation. Details are sparse on the early life of <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, born the daughter of a Baptist minister in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in 1835. She achieved notoriety soon after arriving in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> in 1867, the year <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> became a state. `` The first territorial capitol was between <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Farnam </LOCATION> on Ninth Street, and <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s establishment was right around the corner from it,'' <ORGANIZATION> McNichols </ORGANIZATION> said. Miss <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> met riverboat gambler <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> in 1871. They lived together, unmarried, until he died 1884, and they are buried side-by-side under a large stone slab. The <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> house of prostitution was one of several in the city's old red-light district, a few blocks from the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> adjacent to what is now downtown <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
