<HEAD>Five Dead, Thousands Displaced by Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least five people have died and thousands have been forced to flee their homes because of flooding in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>'s northeastern districts, government officials and news reports said Sunday. Last summer, more than one-quarter of the nation's 105 million people were forced to flee the worst flooding in 70 years. This year, heavy rains and the annual snow melt from the <LOCATION> Himalaya </LOCATION> mountains have sent the <PERSON> Surma </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kushiara </LOCATION> rivers in the northeastern districts of <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sunamganj </LOCATION> over their banks. Government officials in <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION>, 100 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, said Sunday that three people died when their house was washed away and that two others drowned. The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at least 30,000 people have been marooned. Thousands of others made their way to relief camps and were being aided by local <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> officers and government agencies. The government-owned Bengalai-language <ORGANIZATION> Dainik </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bangla </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said at least 500,000 people had been driven from their homes during the past week of rain and flooding. Thousands of acres of tea plantations and rice paddies were reported inundated. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> is a staple food in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. Some market towns in <LOCATION> Sunamganj </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> were reported under two feet of water. Schools in both districts have been closed, and some have been converted to relief centers for the homeless, the officials said. The government officials said flights were disrupted at the airport at <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION> on Saturday. Last year, two months of serious flooding killed about 1,500 people and destroyed thousands of acres of crops.
