<HEAD>Many Soviet Citizens Unfazed By Superpower Summitry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s arrival in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was big news around the world, but thousands of this city's residents seemed oblivious to the historic occasion as they basked in the glorious spring weather. As <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plane touched down in the early afternoon Sunday, the Arbat, a cobbled pedestrian walkway about a mile long, was crowded with people strolling, watching the street artists and standing in line to buy ice cream, shish-kabobs, sundaes, soft drinks and juice. Even the military officials seemed relaxed as they sauntered along the walkway, carrying walkie-talkies as they mingled with pedestrians. Some sat on wooden park benches in the middle of the walkway, which had been decorated with freshly planted flowers. Crowds on the walkway, lined by 16th century houses, were larger than those gathered at the foot of the nearby street leading to <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the home of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON>, where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, are staying. Although Soviet television broadcast the arrival and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s meeting with <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> live, the televisions in the window of an electronics store showed cartoons Another TV set in a crowded snack bar featured a video of <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> gyrating on stage to the tune `` Get Back.'' The Arbat is <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s version of <LOCATION> Montmartre </LOCATION> with scores of street artists drawing portraits in charcoal and oil, where bystanders often crowd around to watch the progression of the work; artists line the street with their work, glow-in-the-dark oil painters, a few restrained nudes and landscapes. Other forms of entertainment on the Arbat are a lone scale, with people lined up to find out their weight and a children's show with large stuffed farm animals _ and a live chicken. The brown bear held a paper summit friendship flag with the stars-and-stripes and the hammer and sickle. Some residents took advantage of Sunday to shop. As usual, there were lines to purchase anything from an ice cream cone to a portion of red sauercraut to a clump of radishes. In some stores, there are two lines: one to pay for an item, the other to pick it up. One popular speciality store served two types of pate, sausage, potato salad and sandwiches. And Soviets apparently are n't adverse to physical shoving when they want to get out of a store or a jam-packed subway car.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The White House advance team handling <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s schedule visited the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> pet market, but decided it was n't the kind of thing the first lady needed to see on her maiden trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The outdoor market is a fascinating slice of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> life: a huge area where people sell dogs, cats, birds, fish, mice, lizards, hamsters, snails and every kind of animal equipment from dog brushes to aquarium cleaners. Held every Saturday and Sunday, the market is definitely not the cleanest place in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, nor the quietest. Debris from stalls that have been torn down litter the area, and the dirt floor was covered with sawdust. All the while, the animals carry on the racket of barking, meowing and tweeting. The Russians carry their pets to the market all kinds of ways. Newborn kittens peer out of gym bags or sleep in cardboard boxes, and puppies play in playpens generally the habitat is children. Birds seem particularly popular. `` People buy them because they are beautiful,'' said the man hawking his white pigeons. One sellers stuffed at least 20 green, yellow and blue parakeets into a cage. The animals, while plentiful, are not cheap. A Siamese kitten cost about $ 64; a pug went for $ 640.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Summit-time means souvenir time, and Soviets are no different from Americans when it comes to hawking items to commemorate the occasion. The Soviets are fans of znockki, lapel pins used to decorate outfits. Summit pins are a hit, and one of the most popular varieties _ costing less than a dollar _ shows an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag and a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> flag forming a `` V.'' `` Mockba-Moscow 1988'' is the inscription. At the Hotel Mezhdunarodnaya, site of the international press center, American-made summit tee-shirts sold like hot-cakes at $ 20 each. The salesgirl said she had sold about 500 in two days. The price did n't deter an Italian reporter who bought eight, charging them to his <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> card. `` What are you going to do?'' he said, explaining his family wanted the souvenirs. `` They wo n't go on sale,'' said one man from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, who did n't want to be quoted by name. `` There are no specials in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>.'' Black sweatshirts with `` perestroikia'' on them, and white ones with a summit designation, were on sale at the Hotel Rossiya, home to many television journalists. They sold for 35 rubles, about $ 56. A European journalist said he ignored the price; he planned to get a higher rate for his rubles by trading hard currency on the black market.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The summit press center is located in a modern hotel complex built in 1980 as an international trade complex. The facility is much like the one the Americans set up at a hotel in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the U.S.-Soviet summit last December. It has banks of telephones and telex printers. Americans and Soviets officials hold press conferences on everything from arms control to the printing of a new book in a cavernous room where reporters sit at long tables, many typing at computers. Reporters use their press passes as collateral to get earphones that provide simultaneous translation in English, Russian, Spanish, French, and German. Soviets waiters sell cheese, salami and ham sandwiches, for a fee, as well as instant coffee _ no milk or cream. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> is dispensed for free, but at one point it ran out. Tables with a range of pamphlets and books on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are available for free. The White House also has a press office at the center, while the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has its own hideaway.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
