<FIRST>r a AM-MagicPiano Bjt   05-29 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Magic Piano, Bjt,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computerized Piano Can Create `Perfect' Performance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is it live? Or is it <PERSON> Bosendorfer </PERSON>? A rocket scientist and a robotics expert using a 9-foot piano have teamed up to create an instrument that can record every flicker of a virtuoso's finger _ and then improve on it. The Bosendorfer 290 SE Imperial Grand looks like a piano next to a computer. But behind the keyboard, optical sensors, tiny electric motors and three linked computers form the guts of a frighteningly accurate musical instrument. Invented by a <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Stahnke </PERSON>, a scientist from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Bosendorfer </PERSON> is played like any piano. Inside, the instruments are recording even microscopic motions. Once the pianist walks away, a punch of a few computer buttons brings forth the performance just played, depressing the piano keys and pedals exactly as the musician did. But the Bosendorfer can also improve on the performance. `` In its most straightforward mode, the piano ` listens' to a live piano performance, ` remembers' that performance note for note and then reproduces that performance _ on the very instrument upon which that performance was played,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Amuedo </PERSON>, a recording engineer who worked on artificial intelligence projects at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. The potential for the $ 100,000 instrument _ a sort of player piano for the computer age _ was immediately apparent to pianist <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moyer </PERSON> and composer-producer <PERSON> Gunther </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuller </PERSON>, who are collaborating on the first recording using the Bosendorfer. Because the piano records its own performance not with microphones but with tiny optical and electronic sensors, the sometimes-disturbing background noise that can crop up at a live performance has no impact on a recording made on the Bosendorfer. A subway car could clatter through the concert hall and it would n't matter Once a performance is over, the hall could be cleared and the performance could be played amid silence. Or the piano could be shipped to a recording studio where the keys could be punched to bring forth the performance with all its spontaneity and energy but none of the background noise. With the push of a few computer keys, the handlers of the Bosendorfer can correct the tiniest of errors _ mistakes inaudible to the human ear but visible among the numbers and symbols on the computer terminal. `` It raises a kind of moral aesthetic question as to how perfect you want to make your recording,'' said <PERSON> Schuller </PERSON>. `` You can make it so perfect that it becomes almost inhuman.'' In March, <PERSON> Moyer </PERSON> performed <LOCATION> Mussorgsky </LOCATION>'s `` Pictures at an Exhibition'' and several short pieces by <PERSON> Mendelssohn </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Wellesley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Afterward, <PERSON> Schuller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amuedo </PERSON> went to work on the editing and found on the computer screen the inevitable tiny errors that even the best of pianists make. <PERSON> Moyer </PERSON>'s performance, the first cassette disc using the Bosendorfer, is to be released this fall on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> Recordings. Amuedo defends the editing capabilities of the instrument as merely improving techniques already widely used by recording engineers. Record producers edit recordings heavily, even live recordings, he argues. The Bosendorfer merely makes the process easier and cleaner. Nor, he said, is the idea of a note-perfect recording anything new, as anyone who has heard a player piano knows. Using existing techniques, a pianist could play a passage beautifully but make one mistake. Correcting the error would require tossing out the well-played section and replaying it. With the Bosendorfer, engineers merely have to plug in the correct note. <PERSON> Schuller </PERSON> also sees the <PERSON> Bosendorfer </PERSON> as an unparalleled teaching tool. Pianists can listen to their own playing exactly as it sounds on the piano. And the computer can slow down a performance without affecting the pitch of a note, allowing pianists to judge their own execution of rapid passages. Amuedo is unconcerned the Bosendorfer will kill the market for live performances, with all their errors. A tiny mistake passes unnoticed in a live performance, he said. On a record that is heard several times, it can become an annoyance. `` No amount of editing is going to salvage a musically bad performance,'' <PERSON> Amuedo </PERSON> said. `` When <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Horowitz </PERSON> gets up and plays, he makes lots and lots of mistakes and yet still people pay $ 20 and $ 30 to hear him play because he makes music out of those mistakes.''
</TEXT>
