<SECOND>AM-Manassas Battle,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suburban Sprawl Threatens Famed Battlefield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A third battle of <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> is brewing, this one over a shopping center complex being built near where the Union and Rebel forces clashed in 1861 and again in 1862. Neither the outrage of preservationists, the pleas of Civil War buffs nor 166 signatures on congressional legislation has been able to stop bulldozers from plowing ground on the project. Construction crews already have begun to lay access roads and prepare the property for sewers. They expect to start construction on the first section of 560 townhouses and detached homes in 60 days. The developers say the section is not part of the land considered sacred by historians. But local preservationists argue that even if the hill from which Confederate Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> directed troops has not yet been touched, the excavation work should stop until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has had time to act. The National <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Battlefield </LOCATION>, about 30 miles from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, is cherished for its bucolic surroundings where visitors can easily imagine what Civil War troops saw in 1861 and 1862 during two of the South's important victories _ the battles of <LOCATION> Manassas </LOCATION>, or as Northerners say, the battles of Bull Run. But the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> metropolitan area is one of the nation's fastest growing regions, and any land around the 4,500-acre historic park not owned by the government is vulnerable to surburban sprawl As for the 600 acres adjacent to the park where <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s troops gathered and battlefield hospitals were located, <ORGANIZATION> Hazel-Peterson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plans to go ahead with construction unless stopped by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, spokesman for the firm, the most prominent development company in northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. A few weeks ago, Reps. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mzarek </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, started action to stop construction by introducing a bill that would have the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary take possession of the land for park expansion. It quickly got the approval of at least 166 members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> who signed on as co-sponsors, but did not win over the three congressmen whose districts comprise northern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. All are Republicans and all are well-acquainted with the wealthy <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> family and its involvement in local <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> politics. In fact, not one of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s 10 members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had signed on in support of the Mzarek-Andrews bill or entered into the debate in any way. Last week, that changed and suddenly there was new hope for historians that the bulldozers would be idled. Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., whose district is near the battlefield, introduced a bill that would enable the government to acquire the land through `` legislative taking,'' a process that is faster than that proposed by <PERSON> Mzarek </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>'s bill also provides for highway construction to relieve traffic congestion threatening the park. Mzarek and <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> quickly gave their support for the plan, and immediately signing on as a co-sponsor was Rep. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parris </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., a longtime friend and partner in some business ventures with <PERSON> John </PERSON> `` Til'' <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON>, who runs <ORGANIZATION> Hazel-Peterson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> Supporting development are county officials who anticipate increased tax revenues. `` We are pleased and happy the project is being built,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Noe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> executive before <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> introduced his bill. `` The greatest hope for stability in the tax base is economic development and a regional mall is the catalyst for the kind of economic development communities need.'' Interior Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> also has opposed congressional intervention, saying the land would cost the government too much. <PERSON> Hazel-Peterson </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said his firm bought the land for between $ 10 million and $ 12 million. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said it probably would cost the government $ 70 million to acquire it. `` Not only is the cost high, but it will not solve the problem, since the proposed mall could simply move further down the road, either imposing a traffic burden on the park or requiring that land also to be purchased,'' said <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> in a letter to Rep. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Udall </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` Development is going to occur all around the battlefield whether it is us or someone else,'' said <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. `` This land is not for sale. We do n't want it taken and we are proceeding with construction.''
