<HEAD>LaserPhotos DT2, NY36</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> named 25 new cardinals from 18 countries Sunday, including prelates from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> in a move to bolster the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Two Americans, Archbishops <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Szoka </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, were on the list. The new `` princes of the church,'' who will be formally elevated at a June 28 Vatican session, bring the number of cardinals to 161. Four new cardinals come from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, two each from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, and one each from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritius </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON>, 67, in a statement in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said he was `` truly honored, very humbled and deeply grateful'' to be chosen. He said he would work with `` all those of good will ... to build a more just and caring community.'' <PERSON> Szoka </PERSON>, 60, told a news conference in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> that he's `` deeply moved and honored'' and will `` carry on the same functions whether I'm cardinal or not.'' In announcing the appointments at the end of a Mass in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basilica </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> noted that the new cardinals come from every continent, reflecting the `` universality'' of the church's 860 million followers Most of the new appointees were heads of large dioceses or <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> departments traditionally held by cardinals. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials described as especially significant the naming of cardinals for <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> stronghold in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, a British colony that reverts to Communist Chinese rule in 1997. `` These were courageous appointments,'' <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> told reporters. `` These are not symbolic choices but options for the future.'' As <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s first publicly named cardinal, the pope chose <PERSON> Vincentas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sladkevicius </PERSON>, 68, the apostolic administrator of <PERSON> Kaisiadorys </PERSON> who was appointed president of the Lithuanian epispocal conference in April. From 1963 to 1982, he was `` impeded'' by Soviet authorities from performing his religious duties and was virtually confined to his residence, according to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sladkevicius </PERSON> becomes the second resident cardinal in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Julijans Vaivods of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> was elevated by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> in 1983. At least 2 million of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s 3.5 million people are estimated to be Roman Catholics. The pope, who has frequently expressed his desire to visit his flock in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, has publicly disclosed that at least on two occasions he has been refused permission to travel to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. The pope moved to bolster the church in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> by elevating <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Baptist </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheng-Chung </PERSON>, the 63-year-old bishop of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. There has been no resident cardinal in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since the Communists took over in 1949. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> cut ties with the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> in 1957 and established a breakway Catholic church, which claims 3 million members. An unknown number of other Catholics remain secretly loyal to the pope, and several are imprisoned for their religious practices. The two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appointments bring to nine the number of American cardinals. Archbishop <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahony </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, 52, was considered for promotion but passed over in what <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> acknowledged was a `` great exclusion'' for the American church. The spokesman said <PERSON> Mahony </PERSON> was not included because of his young age and was likely to become a cardinal at a later time. Named as the first cardinal in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, a Marxist country that the pope will visit during his September tour of southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, was <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>. The Rev. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Urs </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Balthasar </PERSON>, a Swiss theologian highly regarded by the pope, was the only non-bishop among the 25 new cardinals. In addition to voting in a papal conclave, cardinals advise the pope, serve on special <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> commissions and act as spokesmen for the church in their countries. The number of cardinals under the age of 80 and therefore eligible to vote for a new pope will now number 121 _ one more than the limit set by church rules. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> offered no immediate explanation. However, two of the cardinals will turn 80 this summer.
