<HEAD>Authorities And Family Ready For Visit That Didn't Happen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> considered a private visit with a prominent refusenik family Sunday, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources who said the idea was scrubbed when word came that it could hurt the family's chance to emigrate. A honey cake was baked and waiting at the apartment of <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON>, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON>. The Ziemans talked excitedly of how water trucks washed their street clean and workers had daubed fresh paint on their apartment building _ signs that the Soviets were aware of plans for a Reagan visit. But the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> never came. After 11 years of waiting, it was another disappointment. `` When we started to apply to emigrate, I thought it would not be easy for us,'' sighed <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> as she gazed at the crowd on the street. `` The one thing I did n't want to attract is publicity, the mob, like this.'' A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who asked not to be identified said White House planners scrubbed consideration of a Zieman visit after the Soviets passed word that the Ziemans would never leave the country if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> went to their home. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> denied Sunday there ever were definite plans for the <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON> visit, saying only that a number of sites were scouted for potential <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> trips. The Ziemans will be among the refuseniks, the term given to those refused permission to emigrate, meeting with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador's home where the president is staying. Human rights is one of the most contentious issues on the agenda for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s five-day <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit with <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who has vehemently rebutted Western criticism of Soviet human rights policies. Last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> abruptly canceled one of Monday's two planned meetings between <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The discussions had been scheduled to take place between a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> visit to a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> monastery and his meeting with dissidents and refuseniks. The Ziemans are <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Jews who in 1977 first sought permission to emigrate. Several other long-term refuseniks have been granted such permission in recent months, but an estimated 2,000 Soviet Jews have had applications pending. The Ziemans have been notified that they can not leave because <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON>, a computer specialist, would be a risk to Soviet security. They were alerted to a possible visit by the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> last week, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scouting officials came to their home. And they were not the only expectant parties: Soviet officials had cleaned up the neighborhood right up to patching the road and driveway right in front of the apartment. Local militia and plainclothes agents patrolled the area. The Reagans' failure to show clearly disappointed the Ziemans and about 300 curious residents who gathered outside their apartment building, alerted to something unusual by the heavy police presence. After the Ziemans applied to emigrate, <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> lost her job as an English professor and <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> lost his as an advanced computer specialist, working as a hospital plumber until ill health forced him to stop last fall. Their elder daughter, <PERSON> Galya </PERSON>, got out of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> last year, apparently because authorities did not realize from her married name of <PERSON> Khatutsky </PERSON> that she was a member of the <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON> family. She now lives in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, campaigning for her family's emigration. With her perfect British-accented English, curly hair and cherubic cheeks, daughter <PERSON> Vera </PERSON>, 12, charms the many foreigners who visit the Ziemans' three-room apartment. The presidential couple reportedly became interested in the Ziemans' case after <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> wrote to the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> in English on April 4 asking for their help to emigrate. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON>, who is suffering from hepatitis and an undiagnosed condition that gives him double vision, lay on the sofa and discussed his hopes for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> visit. `` If not this visit, I do n't know what will help me,'' he said. `` I think many refuseniks are expecting good news now.'' Hopes traditionally run high amid dissidents and would-be emigres in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> when prominent Western politicians visit, since the Kremlin traditionally solves several or even a few dozen human rights cases during such meetings. On Sunday, very few of those who gathered on the street outside knew the Ziemans or that they are refuseniks. They just knew something unusual was happening. But one elderly lady was convinced <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would never show. `` There are n't enough security around,'' she said. `` If the president was coming, there would be <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> in every doorway.''
