<HEAD>Gorbachev Roots in Provincial Russian City South of Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 16th graf, For 18, to CORRECT dialects to dialectics</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Long before they arrived in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> were the talk of the small city where he began his rise to power. Here, based on interviews with acquaintances, are scenes from the lives of the young <PERSON> Gorbachevs </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAVROPOL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, professor of Marxism-Leninism and wife of the local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, was visibly piqued. For days, gossip had been spreading that she had spent a small fortune on a fur coat. `` When will these rumors stop that my coat cost 12,000 rubles?'' the petite brunette from <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> asked co-workers at the <ORGANIZATION> Stavropol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> one day. `` It was only 608 rubles.'' The long-ago incident, recalled by a former dean of the school where Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> taught, could have happened today. As the wife of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader, Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has been criticized by some Soviets who maintain she embraces Western materialism. It was in the provincial <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> city 850 miles south of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> began their rise to the top of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> hierarchy. The <PERSON> Gorbachevs </PERSON> lived here for 23 years, following their graduation from <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1954. Residents remember seeing the stocky balding <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> _ then the regional party boss _ jogging some mornings along the poplar-shaded streets or in the park opposite his one-story 19th century home at 109 Dzherzhinksy Street. The couple frequented the regional art museum when it held shows from the Hermitage, the <PERSON> Tretyakov </PERSON> or other celebrated Soviet galleries, according to <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendik </PERSON>, then museum director. Those who knew <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in those early years say his flesh-pressing, street-corner brand of politicking took shape in <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION>, as he made his way up through the party ranks in this city of 300,000 people set in the green, rolling hills north of the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. `` He was everywhere, visiting all the stores and enterprises to see what their problems were,'' said <PERSON> Tatyana </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bessyonova </PERSON>, manager of <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION>'s largest store, the Central Universal Store. `` He listened to people's problems, and gave them advice about how to change things.'' The man who would make `` glasnost,'' or openness, an official policy knew by name almost all of the journalists from <LOCATION> Stavropolskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pravda </LOCATION>, the local party newspaper, and would often brainstorm with them, recalled editor-in-chief <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuchmayev </PERSON>. `` He'd come and see us and say, ` Hello, fellows, what's up?''' <PERSON> Kuchmayev </PERSON> said. `` He talked out loud about his thoughts, what he had seen. He did n't order us to print things, but led by example.'' One day when <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was addressing workers at the <LOCATION> Electoavtomatika </LOCATION> electronics plant, the microphone failed. `` Other officials would have crushed bones because of that,'' said plant director <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuznetsov </PERSON>. `` Not <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergeyevich </PERSON>. He pushed aside the microphone and said, ` Fine, comrades, it will be more informal this way.''' For 18 years, Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the Siberian-born daughter of railroad workers, taught Marxist dialectics and historical materialism at the agricultural institute, working on the second floor of a 19th century building where girls of good family were once taught by Russian Orthodox priests. By all accounts, she was a bright, hard-working teacher who demanded much from her students, and also from herself. Every year, Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> taught 180 students in the elements of Marxism-Leninism, delivering lectures in a room with hospital-green walls decorated with large portraits of <LOCATION> Descartes </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kant </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hegel </PERSON> and other philosophers. She was paid 320 rubles a month, about $ 500. Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was once grabbed by a guard after she entered the institute. He had mistaken her for a student, and wanted her to leave her coat in the student's cloakroom, recalled the former dean, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chuguyev </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Pankratovich </PERSON>, when are people going to recognize the fact that I work here and am not a student?'' <PERSON> Chuguyev </PERSON> recalls her saying. Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, working at a beaten wooden desk now decorated with a single rose in a vase, taught philosophy from the ancient Greek times to the present. Her courses were mandatory for economic majors. `` She was respected greatly because she was the best prepared ... The rest of us went to her lectures to see how they should be done,'' <PERSON> Chuguyev </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself entered the institute as a part-time student in 1962-68, working towards a degree as an `` advanced agro-economist,'' a speciality important for someone keen on rising in the party hierarchy in the farming region of <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION>. `` He asked for no special treatment, and was interested in pursuing the truth to the very end,'' remembers <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamensky </PERSON>, dean of part-time students at the institute and a friend of the Gorbachevs for decades. One day, in the midst of a four-hour chemistry experiment, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was whisked away by a limousine on urgent party business. But he returned later in the day, telling <PERSON> Kamensky </PERSON>, `` I want to finish the experiment by myself and see the results.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was born in 1931 to a peasant family in <LOCATION> Privolnoye </LOCATION>, a village on the black-earth steppes about 100 miles north of the <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> regional center. With his <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law diploma in his pocket, he returned to <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> in 1954 as an intern in the prosecutor's office But he was snapped up by the <ORGANIZATION> Komsomol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> youth league, and began a career that included stints as local <LOCATION> Komsomol </LOCATION> leader, party boss for the city of <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> and party chief for the <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> region, an area about the size of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. When <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was named regional party chief in 1970, <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> went to her superiors at the agricultural institute, and asked not to be named head of the philosophy department, a promotion for which she had been in line. `` People will say that I've been promoted because of my husband,'' she told her co-workers. `` Not because of what I've done.
