</LOCATION> assumes the Soviets will abide by their agreement, signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, to pull their forces out of the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> nation. Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> characterized the opening round of talks as businesslike and cordial, but he offered few details. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> charged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> does not have a `` concrete understanding'' of the human rights issue in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and objected to others lecturing Soviets on how to conduct their affairs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s position `` is based on the past and does not take into consideration what is happening today,'' the spokesman said, apparently referring to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s somewhat more tolerant emigration policies and `` glasnost,'' which permits broader but still limited criticism of Soviet officialdom and society. The Foreign Ministry official said his government knew about its drawbacks. `` We are trying to correct'' them, <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> added, `` but we don ` t like it when someone else is making us feel like a pupil.'' During a picture-taking session at the outset of his first meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was asked if he intended to lecture his counterpart on human rights. `` I have no intention of trying to be a teacher,'' he said. <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, searching for ways to continue the improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations, suggested the superpowers might launch a joint manned mission to Mars or participate in an international conference or seminal on human rights. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been cool to both Soviet initiatives in the past. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, discussing the failure to reach agreement before the summit on nuclear testing and other pacts nearing completion, told <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Meet the Press'' that their not being signed in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> `` underscores the careful and prudent way the administration is approaching this. Detail can kill you _ literally _ if you do n't get it right.
