<HEAD>French Journalist Returns Home; Report Says Italian To Be Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> journalist returned home to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on Sunday after nine months in `` absolutely deplorable conditions'' in an Afghan jail. A newspaper said an Italian journalist jailed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> would soon be freed. <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON> was convicted on spy charges and sentenced to 10 years in prison in January. He was pardoned Friday and freed Saturday. The French <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper L'Humanite made available a report from its <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> correspondent saying that Italian journalist <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON> `` may be freed within two or three days.'' The report was for Monday's edition of the newspaper. <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON> spent part of his detention with <PERSON> Biloslavo </PERSON>, who was arrested in July and sentenced to seven years in prison. <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON> was arrested in August after entering <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> with guerrillas who are fighting the Soviet-backed government. `` The conditions of detention were rough, absolutely deplorable,'' Guillo, 45, told reporters at <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gaulle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> early Sunday. It was `` nine months of complete isolation,'' except for rare visits from the French charge d'affaires, he said. `` But it was nothing compared to the others. There is an Italian journalist, Turkish, Iranian, Pakistani prisoners. Their life is a real hell. They have no contact with their families. They are cut from the world.'' Guillo is an independent photojournalist who often worked for the Sygma agency covering the 10-year-old civil war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The secretary-general of the French <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Perol </PERSON>, stressed that obtaining his release should not be construed as an element of political negotiations with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Guillo's liberation was accompanied by `` no conditions, no commitment of any sort,'' <PERSON> Perol </PERSON> said. `` We have settled the Guillo case. Period.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that the release followed a written request from <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to Afghan President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and expressed hope for improved relations. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> maintains relations with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> but has made clear it does not support the government. Guillo is the sixth Frenchman jailed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since 1979. In each case, a pardon was eventually granted. Guillo was captured August 28 while traveling with members of the Afghan resistance on his ninth reporting trip to the country since 1979. His arrest was announced in September. On Jan. 4, he was sentenced to 10 years in prison for espionage and subversive activities. `` For 15 days, they -LRB- Afghan police -RRB- hesitated between killing me on the spot and arresting me formally,'' he told reporters Saturday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dehli </LOCATION>, where he stopped en route to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` They would have blamed the killing on the mujahedeen.'' The Afghan rebels call themselves mujahedeen, or holy warriors. <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON> called his trial `` pure comedy and a travesty of justice.'' In a televised interview with <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> journalists earlier this month, <PERSON> Guillo </PERSON> said he would never ask for a pardon because he was not guilty and considered himself a hostage.
