<HEAD>Letterman Writers _ `Vacation' Soon Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For most of the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the 2 -LCB- - month-old strike has been a stressful time of picket lines, union meetings, no paychecks and lost creative opportunity For the writers of `` Late Night with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON>,'' being on strike has been, well, not that different from going to work. `` We sleep till noon,'' said head writer <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>, `` get up, drink some coffee, go down to the Writers Guild, see if anything's going on, then we go home. But now, during the strike ...'' Until one-liners earn them money again _ which should be soon, since `` Late Night'' has reached a tentative independent agreement with the guild _ the show's writers have been offering them in magazine pieces or interviews with reporters looking for that missed-monologue angle on the strike story. The show has been in reruns since the strike started March 7. <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>, joined by `` Late Night'' staffers <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON>, reminisced Friday about a typical day of work at the show. `` We come down to beautiful, almost-landmark Rockefeller Center at 9:30 or 10 and linger until it's quite dark outside,'' said <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>. `` It's hand-to-mouth. We're usually working on the next day's show, if not that day's show, the day of the broadcast. So that's why we're not too worried about stockpiling things up. Sometimes our days are not too miserable, because sometimes a lot of our writing consists of a sentence. Something like ...'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>: `` ` Let's go up and talk to our audience.''' `` Perfect,'' says <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>. `` See, then we knock off and go get the thickest steak in town. ... Or other times, it will just be a phrase, a concept, a man, a plan, a canal, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>: `` ` <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> says something funny.''' <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>: `` ` <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> takes bullhorn to window and tries to get pedestrian to bring him up a hot dog.' Then we look at each other and say, ` That's it, that's it. Who's for dessert?''' But now, there are picket lines to walk. `` There is like just a minimum of actual union activities,'' said <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>. `` We go picketing once a week. `` I think people passing by as they see these writers in their not-very-solid-looking picket lines, I think they have a series of thoughts _ the first is, do writers have a union? And then, do they work that hard? And then perhaps the last stage is, wait a second. TV writers get paid plenty! `` I do n't think a lot of people understand the strike was n't for more money, it was to keep royalties from being cut back.'' `` Wait a second,'' said <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, `` it was n't for more money?'' `` What the hell have we been doing?'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, who has been playing golf. But seriously. `` We certainly support the guild,'' said <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>. `` If it was n't for them, we'd certainly be in bad shape. But the actual issues in this strike do not pertain to late-night comedy writers.'' `` It's a nice little vacation,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. But life on strike means missing important events in the life of `` Late Night.'' Just that morning, the local papers were splashed with <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON>'s smiling file-photo face next to headlines about a `` mystery woman'' driving his car who told officials at the <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tunnel </LOCATION>, where she did n't have the toll, that she was `` Mrs. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Letterman </PERSON>.'' `` Usually <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> has to go on a murder spree to make the front page of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. And he recommends, `` if you're going to steal <PERSON> Dave </PERSON>'s car, please, please have correct change.''
