<HEAD>Hawks Warn Labor Party Risking Elections By Veering Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some politicians in Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> fear that a newly chosen slate of dovish candidates could cost them the national elections in November. Their concern was triggered by a meeting of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday in which more than half of 29 candidates chosen to run for parliament favor making more concessions to the Arabs for peace than the party has advocated in the past. The party's dovish turn appears to contradict a recent shift in <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> public opinion polls, which show a majority support right-wing Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and his allies in espousing a tougher stand toward the Arabs. `` I am definitely worried by the change. The fact is, more doves than expected were elected, and this will harm us very much in the elections,'' Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Aryeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehamkin </PERSON> said. Those on Labor's new slate include several peace activists and a former ultra left-wing legislator, <PERSON> Lova </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliav </PERSON>, who has had contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and has advocated a full Israeli pullout from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The latest public opinion poll, taken this month and published May 13 by the Yediot Ahronot daily, showed <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> and allied parties winning 59 seats. The Likud and its allies were predicted to win 61. After <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s last elections, in 1984, the Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> parties formed a coalition in which <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> served as prime minister for the first two years and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> for the past two years. Political analysts say Israelis' swing to the right reflects a hawkish public mood stirred by the six-month-old Palestinian uprising in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The analysts say that the Labor infighting could further damage the party's electoral image by presenting a confused picture to the public. `` With such a fractious and contradictory slate it will be difficult to formulate an attention-grabbing campaign to compete with parties either to the left or the right,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Margalit </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION> daily. The doves and hawks in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> are divided over how to implement a plank in its platform which calls for giving up some land occupied in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> War in exchange for peace with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states. The hawks favor a formula which would leave <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> with the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, a stand unacceptable to Arabs. They also completely reject negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. Labor's newest candidates have a more lenient approach to territorial compromise and some favor talking with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> if it officially recognizes <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` I think that Labor is back where it should be, on the road of looking for peace, that peace has a price and you do n't get it without compromising,'' said Russian-born <PERSON> Lova </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliav </PERSON>, 66. He predicted a tough Israeli election campaign over the peace issue. `` People are extreme, dangerously so. I think it's time for voters to choose a party that wants to tak