UPDATE with Soviet TV coverage on Vremya, Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet press said Sunday that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had made a `` turnaround'' on East-West relations in the past three years, resulting from a fresh look at changing world realities rather than a reversal of his staunch anti-communist views. One commentator said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has high hopes for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s fourth summit meeting with <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, but another said progress will depend largely on whether <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s approach is `` realistic and constructive. Soviet television pre-empted regular programming for a live broadcast of the president's arrival at <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Vnukovo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and his initial meeting with the Soviet leader in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>. An expanded, 90-minute version of the evening news program `` Vremya'' devoted a full 52 minutes to the summit, rerunning much of the welcoming ceremony at the airport and the speeches by both leaders. It also carried more than two minutes on <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s tour of the Cathedral of the Assumption conducted by <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, giving rare prominence to the wife of a Soviet leader `` Vremya'' carried a lengthy interview with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> adviser <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and director of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. He dis