h representative of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that would sign a Soviet-U.S. intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty and moreover, bring to the Soviet capital the first document on nuclear arms reduction in history, ratified by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Senate.'' `` Does it mean that the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> leader has changed his views?'' <PERSON> Biryukov </PERSON> asked. `` Perhaps it would be more correct to describe this turnaround as a result of understanding the fact that the world has changed and that the interests of our countries are changing. And the president has probably taken a fresh look at the existing realities without giving up his known views.'' <PERSON> Biryukov </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` pins its most serious hopes'' on the summit meeting. Pravda said summit progress depends largely on `` how realistic and constructive'' is <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s approach. <PERSON> Biryukov </PERSON> wrote that since the December summit talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not allowed any progress toward agreement on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> plan for a space-based shield against nuclear attack. The Soviets regard the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> as a violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
