<HEAD>St. Bernard High Schools Going Co-Ed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHALMETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The valedictorian at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> was a bit wistful at last week's graduation as he recalled some of the problems his class faced at one of the parish's single-sex secondary schools During freshman year, the boys in his class had to cope with intimidation from upperclassmen, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Zanco </PERSON> said. `` In our sophomore year, we had another problem to deal with _ females. They were everywhere but in the school,'' he said. <PERSON> Zanco </PERSON>'s successor will be spared that lament because next year the four high schools in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> in suburban <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> will go co-educational for the first time in a generation. The change was sparked by a lawsuit won last year by a parent last year who wanted his son and daughter to attend the same school. <PERSON> Hilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>'s suit said his children were victims of discrimination because they were n't being taught the same things. Calls to Wall's home went unanswered Sunday. Court-ordered racial desegregation of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> schools helped lead to the sexual segregation of St. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON>'s high schools 22 years ago. The parish was a magnet for so-called `` white flight'' from the inner city, and the population boom strapped the school board's budget To economize, school officials decided to split high schools by sex, building sports stadiums at boys' schools and home economics labs at girls schools. `` At the time, we thought we were doing the taxpayers a service,'' <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> said. `` It all went off quite well. In those days, there were n't many boys trying to be cheerleaders. And being a secretary was still thought of as a job for girls. So there was no reason to have a big stenographic lab for boys _ they just were n't going to sign up for it.'' School Board President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said the reversion to co-education wo n't be cheap. A no-frills conversion _ modifying bathrooms, adding extra equipment and duplicating courses _ will cost the board about $ 300,000, he said. `` Financially, it's going to be devastating this year,'' <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said. `` But the staff is ready. And the kids are ready.'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a supervisor with St. Bernard Parish schools, looked forward to the change. `` It teaches kids to socialize better. And it's my personal observation that students tend to behave a bit better,'' he said.
