<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Men firing submachine guns kidnapped a newspaper executive and former Conservative presidential candidate Sunday and killed his bodyguard. <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON>, 69, the son of former President <PERSON> Laureano </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>, was seized as he left church. The abduction came during a wave of leftist guerrilla violence, including the kidnapping of three mayors-elect of small towns, two ambushes that left seven soldiers dead, and guerrilla attacks on two towns and an oil pipeline. <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>'s family issued a statement confirming the kidnapping. Some radio stations reported the family said <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> had been wounded, but the statement did not say that. The statement appealed for medical attention for <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> in case he had been wounded. An anonymous person claiming to be one of the kidnappers called the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> radio station Todelar. Then a voice sounding like <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said in Spanish, `` Oh, oh, I'm dying.'' <PERSON> Todelar </PERSON> played a recording of the telephone call. President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, on a state visit to <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, said in a statement that he ordered all government security forces to search for <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> was leaving the church across from the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> on a broad, tree-lined street in the northern part of the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> capital when the kidnappers jumped him. `` I had said goodbye -LRB- to <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> -RRB- and had walked maybe 15 steps when I heard the sound of submachine guns,'' said a former federal senator, <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Palacio </PERSON>. `` I hit the ground and then I saw four men pushing him into a car,'' <PERSON> Palacio </PERSON> said in an interview with radio