<HEAD>Test Burn, Delayed Once More, Now Facing Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Army once again postponed the test burn of a Pershing II rocket motor Sunday and will have to conduct the test by Tuesday or face a further 30-day delay, officials said. The test burn is an important step in imposing terms of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, which calls for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to eliminate medium-range missiles. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Pueblo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Activity </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officials were told they have until 5 p.m. Tuesday to finish the test or it will have to be postponed under the INF treaty. `` After the treaty enters into force, all assets of both countries covered by the treaty would be frozen for 30 days,'' she said. `` The test must then be treated as an elimination and done according to provisions of the treaty.'' The INF treaty was ratified Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Friday and by the Soviet Presidium on Saturday. The treaty is expected to be formalized by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> during the current <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit and will be in force Wednesday. Adverse weather conditions have forced repeated postponements since the originally scheduled test date of May 20. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said an absence of wind led to Sunday's postponement. On Saturday, instability in the upper winds and a threat of thunderstorms forced officials to call off the test. The Army is aiming for a test burn at about 6:30 a.m. Monday, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. If the test is n't completed by Tuesday, a Soviet delegation probably would be allowed to monitor the test under the INF treaty, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. The test burn is needed to determine the suitability of the Pueblo site for destroying the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s 420 Pershing missiles to comply with the INF treaty.
