<HEAD>Two Russian Dancers Appear with Ballet Theater</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With two principal dancers from <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>'s Kirov Ballet in starring roles and the American Ballet Theater company in top form, a full-length performance of `` La Bayadere'' made for an electric evening <PERSON> Altynai </PERSON> <PERSON> Assylmuratova </PERSON> and <PERSON> Farukh </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruzimatov </PERSON> are the first Soviet dancers to guest with American Ballet Theater. `` La Bayadere'' was first performed in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> in 1877. It was staged and choreographed, after <PERSON> Marius </PERSON> <PERSON> Petipa </PERSON>, for American Ballet Theater by <PERSON> Natalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Makarova </PERSON> in 1980. Miss <PERSON> Makarova </PERSON>, who was a <LOCATION> Kirov </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ballet </LOCATION> dancer before she defected to the West, at that time danced the part of <LOCATION> Nikiya </LOCATION>, the temple dancer or bayadere. On Saturday night, <PERSON> Ruzimatov </PERSON> danced the role of the warrior Solor, who falls in love with the bayadere, performed by <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Assylmuratova </PERSON>. Then the <PERSON> Radjah </PERSON> introduces Solor to his daughter to be his bride and Solor falls for her beauty. When <PERSON> Ruzimatov </PERSON> entered the stage, he was a coiled spring _ a slim, lithe man about to burst with energy. An entrance of such contained excitement has seldom been seen since <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Nureyev </PERSON> was young. <PERSON> Ruzimatov </PERSON> lived up to that promise with his turns in air, the elevation of his jumps and the beauty of his technique. Miss <PERSON> Assylmuratova </PERSON> has splendid technique also, and her duet and solo dancing dazzled. However, she seemed tense instead of conveying freedom as she flew across the stage. One expects her to relax more for her second performance. Also, she did n't convey the acting part of her role as <PERSON> Ruzimatov </PERSON> did his. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> danced the Radjah's daughter. She held her own in what must have seemed daunting company. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> was very effective as the High Brahmin who also loves the bayadere and whose mime gestures help move the plot. <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Renvall </PERSON> was the third act's bronze idol and did his solo in a dignified way instead of making it look silly. The second act, in the Kingdom of the Shades, is all of `` La Bayadere'' usually seen in this country. Its soothing beauty rests on the corps de ballet's being able to move in unison and to hold long, difficult balances. On Saturday night, Ballet Theater's corps de ballet was exquisite.
