<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is it live? Or is it <PERSON> Bosendorfer </PERSON>? A rocket scientist and a robotics expert using a 9-foot piano have teamed up to create an instrument that can record every flicker of a virtuoso's finger _ and then improve on it. The Bosendorfer 290 SE Imperial Grand looks like a piano next to a computer. But behind the keyboard, optical sensors, tiny electric motors and three linked computers form the guts of a frighteningly accurate musical instrument. Invented by a <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Stahnke </PERSON>, a scientist from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Bosendorfer </PERSON> is played like any piano. Inside, the instruments are recording even microscopic motions.
