<FIRST>r f AM-SmellofSuccess     05-29 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smell of Success,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents of Illinois Town Endure Stench to Stock Nation's
Cupboards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOOPESTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The smell of success stinks, say some residents of this east-central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> town whose canneries supply food that stocks the nation's cupboards. Each spring residents await the return of noxious fumes that waft off water used to process beans and corn at two local canneries that support the town's economy. `` I just tell people it only hurts your nose, it does n't hurt your lungs,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Hoopeston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> official Rose Buck. `` That's the smell of success.'' Millions of gallons of the contaminated water are sprayed irrigation-style onto nearby fields until winter weather arrives. Warm temperatures release the vapors and winds carry them around and into the town of 6,400 residents. While canning company officials say special equipment has helped, the odor leaves many breathless. `` There is nothing more offensive than the bean water,'' said <LOCATION> Hoopeston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Councilman <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON>, who farms near the ponds sitting along <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Rts. 1 and 9. `` You do n't get used to it. You just hope you're not in that field too long.'' But the putrid smell _ best described as rotting vegetables _ represents money in the bank for the townspeople. Two century-old <LOCATION> Hoopeston </LOCATION> canneries _ owned by <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury-Joan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Stokely </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ employ hundreds of local residents and pump millions of dollars into the area's economy. Thousands more migrant seasonal workers are hired each year to help with the fall harvest. `` If we do n't have that smell, we would be in trouble,'' <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> said, adding that most Americans probably do n't realize what <PERSON> Hoopeston </PERSON> endures to keep canned goods in the nation's grocery stores. `` They do n't even know where a can of beans comes from. They do n't know where milk comes from, or how much work is done to keep the beans clean,'' he said. Nine types of beans come into the Pillsbury-Joan of Arc plant dry and must be washed and then soaked and softened in water. Most of the water is then discarded. The rehydrated beans, including kidney, garbanzo and black-eyed peas, are sold to consumers nationwide under the Joan of Arc and other labels, and used in chili sold by the <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s hamburger chain. Plant Manager <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kortkamp </PERSON> of Pillsbury-Joan of Arc says the company invested in a $ 1 million, state-of-the-art water reclamation facility three years ago that eliminated much of the odor. The system strains the larger bean parts out, then pumps the water into tanks where microscopic organisms eat much of the remaining bean matter. `` I'm talking about a relative smell,'' <PERSON> Kortkamp </PERSON> said. `` On a scale of one to 10 we have improved it to an eight or nine.'' But some odor remains, <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> said. `` After they have processed it two or three times, then it gets into that big lagoon out there. Then they spray it into the air and it gets a little rank,'' he said. In the fall, fumes from water used to process sweet corn contribute to the odor problem. Pungent corn water then is sprayed onto fields north of town. <PERSON> Stokely </PERSON> sells the corn and a variety of other canned goods under its label. While the scent might annoy some vistors, many long-time residents say it's all in the nose. `` That does n't stink,'' a <LOCATION> Hoopeston </LOCATION> policeman said when asked about the smell. `` I've lived here all my life and I'm used to it.''
</TEXT>
