<SECOND>AM-Rawlings-Helmets,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rawlings Getting Out Of Helmet Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Rawlings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has announced that it is getting out of the football helmet business, citing increased liability and `` skyrocketing'' insurance costs. The company will continue to manufacture football equipment from the neck down and will also continue to make non-competitive replica helmets, <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said Friday. <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON>' departure from the helmet business leaves only two major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers _ <ORGANIZATION> Riddell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and A.H.I. Corp. of <LOCATION> Litchfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON> has explored options to make it practical and profitable to remain in the helmet business, but can no longer justify the manufacture of competitive football helmets,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. Litigation involving head and neck injuries was the major factor in the decision, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. In the past 15 years there have been about 25 helmet liability cases tried in court and verdicts have been granted totaling around $ 46 million, he said. Since 1980, the total has been $ 39 million. <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON> made its competitive helmets at <LOCATION> Ava </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. The helmets were one-piece shells of polycarbonate plastic. Most of the company's sales of competitive helmets has been to high schools and colleges, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said.
